Apache Kafka(event,log,history)

	- Apache Kafka is an open-source distributed event streaming platform
	- Open-source- Its freely available to use
	- distributed - It can run in ditributed environment
	- event-streaming - Is a way of producing and consuming data
	
		e.g. Media House and reporter
		e.g. Coffee shop (Customer,Cashier,chef,waiter)
			- Customer orders coffe then cashier takes order and notify chef and waiter
			- imagine there is rush of customer in a shop the above way is not feasible because each time cashier will not go and inform chef and waiter
			- After Order placed event no one is listening to the event 
			- let's say there is digital board in restaurant , once order placed, the cashier push the order to digital display, so chef and waiter are watching that, customer will have token number for that
			- Hence rush is avoided
		e.g. Postman checking to deliver letter multiple times, we can avoid this by postbox
	- No direct communication is needed, hence anyone can leave and join without disturbing others
		
	- Kafka helps by
		- Decoupling services ( if we have multiple chefs the process will be same , chefs will keep checking digital board)
		- Scalability
		- Replayability
		- Efficiency
		
		
  -> Event streaming means continuosly capturing events( data) in real-time, storing them in a 
  	log(like timeline- logs will always appended at end.There are multiple log files created so that parallel processing happens, related logs go in one log file.  )
  	and allowing systems to react to them either immediately or later
  	
  -> Producer -> Cashier
  -> Events(orders) -> stored in cafka(Digital board)
  -> Consumer (chef, waiter)
  
  -> we can take example of zomato as well user placed order -> restaurant will be notified, delivery agent will be notified
  
  -> Event means passing data, is event streaming is only way to pass data not really
  
  	- Request/Response - One system calls another and waits for reply e.g. REST API, HTTP
  	- Batch processing - System processes large chunks of data at intervals e.g. Nightly data imports, reports
  	- Message Queues - One system sends a messge to a queue, another pulls from it. e.g. RabbitMQ,SQS
  	- Event Streaming - Systems send and react to a constants flow of events. Kafka, pulsar
  	
  	
  -> Kafka like WhatsApp Group
  
  	- people sending messages are producers
  	- peaople reading messages are consumer
  	- Group chat are Kafka topic
  	- There are more than one groups we have so each group is kafka topic
  	- work topic, friends topic -> we will send related messages to to related group because we know who all are consumer means reader of that group so we will push related messages
  	- Even if one of the member of group is offline he will not miss the message, once he is back online he will receive message
  	-  like10 consumer listening to topic if three are  offline , the message is not lost, they will start consuming from where they left 
  	
  	- messages are stored in order, so coversation flow will not be missed
  	- Multiple consumer consumes same messages
  	
  	
  	
  	RabbitMQ vs Kafka
  	
  	Model They are operating 
  		- Kafka operates on event streaming model which is based on logs
  		- RabbitMQ works on Message Queuing model
  	Message Storage
  	
  		- Kafka keeps all the messages for mentioned period of time, so consumer can reread
  		- RabbitMQ deletes message after it's consumed
  		
  	Consumers 
  		- in Kafka Each consumer group can read individually
  				Consumer Group : we can group consumer together which is consumer group
  		- RabbitMQ messages are removed from queue once message is delivered
  	
  	Best For 
  	
  		- Kafka is best suitable for High-throughput, real-time analytics, data replay
  			-Throughput: A rate at which messages are processed
  		- RabbitMQ useful for Task Queuing, short lived jobs
  		
  	Persistence 
  		- Designed for long term storage and replay
  		- RabbitMQ focused on short term delivery
  		
  	Ordering of event
  	
  		- Kafka Guarantees order of events within a partition
  		- RabbitMQ has no strict ordering unless manually handled
  		
  	Throughput
  	
  		- Kafka has very high throughput(designed for streaming big data)
  		- RabbitMQ has moderate
  		
  		
